social_posts.post_text:
Almost entirely straight out of camera, believe it or not.  This location, this day, and these two were just perfect.
.
With @suzannefiore

What is one change you made in your photographic process that saved you both time and peace of mind? This is what @scottwyden asked world-renowned photographer @susanstriplingphotography in the first episode of Season 2 of our podcast, ‘Workflows’. ⁠
⁠
Do you agree with Susan’s approach—or do you prefer to play it on the safe side by overshooting? Share your thoughts and opinions in the comments below!
⁠
⤴ Head to link in bio to listen to the full episode with Susan Stripling ⤴⁠
⁠
#Workflows #PhotographyPodcast #PhotographyTips #PhotographyTricks #PhotographyBusiness #PhotographySkills

I just booked my travel - St. Thomas here we come.  I can't wait to document more of these two - next time in warmer weather!
.
With @suzannefiore

I generally don't love "from the archives" posts.  It feels dusty, nostalgic in an odd way, a little strange to page through the catalog of old work.
.
As I get ready for the 2023 season I am wildly grateful to be able to take a month off.  My love and I will be road-tripping our way out west and back, and weddings won't start back up again until we get back.
.
I was updating my portfolio Lightroom catalog and decided to take a deeeeep dive backwards to watch my skills improve as the years go by.  And when I tell you I got LOST in there...I really did.  So many memories, not just of past clients but of my past self.  The person I was, the person I am now.
.
So maybe the archives aren't such a bad place to visit...perhaps I should do it more often.
.
(Shot in 2014.)

I remember when I first started using off-camera flash.  I was SO scared of it - what settings do I use on the flash?  Where do I actually PUT it?  What about camera settings? 
.
Things started so so slow.  I took a one-light workshop from @zarias that set me on my way.  I started learning how to put together the pieces: decide on the vibe of the image, set my ambient settings first, then use flash to place light just where I want it. 
.
From there it was about control.  I started using diffusers, @magnetmod grids, and sometimes even more than one light.
.
I always ask myself "if I had the sun here, where would I want it?" And that's where the light goes.  At the end of the day it's as simple as that!

The sweetest proposal on a cold, cold winter day.
.
Lit by the Dyker Heights lights and a little @stellaprolights magic.  Bonus points go to the darling pompom hats and jacket fur.

The most beautiful, extraordinary, sublime talent. @alistroker is a glorious human inside and out.
.
Natural light in my old living room studio in Brooklyn.

A very oldie but a super goodie.
.
This deep dive through my back catalog of work has been fascinating.  I can practically SEE my photographic eye evolving.  This image is one of the first ones where I saw a concept in real-time and made it happen.
.
I was looking out the window of the wedding venue and admiring the skyline. While I was doing that someone opened a door at the back of the reception space and a bright white rectangle cut into the skyline reflection. I immediately ran and asked my couple if they would be willing to snuggle up in that open doorway, and the rest is history.
.
I used to be nervous to ask my clients to do something out of the ordinary. I used to look at weddings with such limited focus, not understanding that if I looked around me there would be so much more to see.
.
Shot in 2011.

My favorite first look reaction ever.
.
Some couples just wedge their way into your heart and stay there for ages to come.  I've followed this man and his wife as they married, had two gorgeous children, and navigated life as a team.
.
Sometimes it really does blow my mind, the longevity of the career I've had and the people who have let me into their lives time and time again.

New York in the winter is....gross.  Slush-filled sneak-attach ankle-deep steps off of sidewalks aren't the most fun.  New York in the summer smells like old feet and the humidity is always a surprise. 
.
However, New York in the spring and fall?  THAT is the New York that lured me in and made me fall in love.  Nothing is better than Central Park when the leaves are golden, the air is crisp with winter-is-coming, and I once again realize that sunrise engagement sessions are the best.

How I feel about window light: a haiku:
.
I love you I love
you I love you I love you
I love you so much

I've been so busy with weddings and life over the past year that personal projects have somewhat fallen to the wayside. Both of my daughters are now in college, and restructuring what my daily life looks like has been more of a challenge than I anticipated.
.
I remember this gorgeous session as if it was yesterday. Getting to collaborate with some of my favorite humans was a joy that I need to remember not to forget. Sometimes it's really important to go play with the craft that you have chosen for your career. 
.
Revisiting this image has reminded me of that.

Found moments.  My favorite thing.
.
It's impossible to tell you what cracks me up the most here.  Is it the dad and younger sister TOTALLY ignoring the flower girl?  Is it the sassypants on the coffee table attempting to command attention?  The formal wear juxtaposed against the totally organic moment?
.
Either way, this image has made me snicker since 2016!

Shallow depth of field. 
.
When I started photography I was instructed to make sure that everything was in focus. From the subject to the background, keep everything sharp and clear!
.
Over time I realized that I did not love that approach. While it worked sometimes, other times I wanted the main subject to pop more. Or I wanted the background to take on an abstract look. Or this or that, how to achieve it?
.
I started photographing with shallow depth of field pretty quickly into my career. Now I am simply obsessed with it. My favorite lens is currently my RF 50mm f/1.2. I love the relationship that the shallow depth of field creates between my chosen subject and the foreground or/and background of the frame.
.
This image is a pretty classic example of that. Taken on a suite deck of the Bowery Hotel, the Manhattan skyline becomes a gorgeous blur behind the couple.
.
(Also @canonusa has my 135mm shipped yet?  I canNOT wait for this mega awesome upgrade to an old favorite. #iamready #giveittome#135mmforLIFE)

Queen Emmy the awesome.
.
The nicest, funniest, most stunning human, it's been a joy to know you but FAR too long since I've last seen you!
.
In the studio bringing the @murphymade MORE HAZE to life.

I have never seen a barn like THIS before. 
.
I talked a lot here about my love for off-camera flash. However, I have to be careful that I don't default to artificially lighting EVERY SINGLE portrait that I take. One of my favorite types of natural light can be seen in this image. It involves standing my subject in an open doorway with the light falling off into the dark space behind them. 
.
The key is to step my subject just out of the bright light and just into the doorway. I don't want strong light hitting them, I want that gentle falloff. Then once I've exposed properly for my subject the rest of the space will darken down as the light drops off into the building.
.
Once again tho, CAN WE TALK ABOUT THE LIGHT FIXTURES IN THIS BARN?

I heard a photographer once say that they capture over 15,000 frames per wedding.
.
I used to think that was something for me to aspire to.  Until I realized that for me?  It wasn't.
.
So I started shooting LESS.  Like...a lot less.  I was photographically raised on "spray and pray"...shoot and shoot and shoot and you won't miss a moment!  For me, tho?  If I'm machine-gunning the shutter I'm not paying attention at all.
.
I started waiting and watching instead.  As a result my number of frames decreased massively but my hit rate? Went way up.  By slowing down I saw MORE.
.
This was a single capture.  Once the wind kicked up the veil I waited until it hit the peak of flight and clicked - done.  I got 2-3 more frames as it floated down but if I'd been leaning on the shutter I could have missed THIS.
.
What about you?  Shoot a lot or a little?  What works best for YOU is what you should do - there is no right or wrong in wedding photography at all!

A favorite moment from a shoot with a favorite subject.  Jenna, you're a gem.  Congratulations on baby Rome!
.

Relationships.
.
I work on my website a lot. An awful lot. I get quite a few clients from Google, so my online presence is incredibly important to me. I also work hard on social media and various other types of online marketing.
.
That said, absolutely nothing takes the place of happy clients and personal referrals. This lovely woman was my first client out from this incredible family. In the years following I photographed several weddings for these amazing people. They brought me out to Wisconsin time and time again and thinking about it still humbles me to this day.
.
I try so hard to take care of my clients, give them an excellent experience, and be the kind of warm and lovely human that they want to spend time around again and again. To anyone reading this that has ever referred me to anyone, please know that it did not go unnoticed. Thank you from the depths of everything.

I've heard a lot of wedding photographers say things like "oh I'm not tempted by the cake, I'm not much of a cake person."
.
Friends,  I am a CAKE.  PERSON.  Whether you have cupcakes or a large cake or a small cake or a fake cake with a real topper or donuts or basically any kind of baked good at your wedding I would very politely like to request some of it.
.
Here are some of my very favorite cakes.
.
(Goes to go eat cake now because I suddenly really, really want it.)

I photographed this image of my very sweet friends Amy and Brandon while the entire wedding photography process was streamed live on Facebook for @theweddingschool.
.
I didn't go into photography intending to be an educator. After a handful of years of photographing destination weddings, I was asked by a local camera group to speak about the process. That led to another speaking engagement and another, eventually culminating at PPA and WPPI as well as Creative Live.
.
In 2016 I launched my own online wedding photography education platform, The Wedding School. Creating that remains one of the accomplishments in my career that I am the proudest of. I worked extraordinarily hard on it for a handful of beautiful long years.
.
During the pandemic of 2020 forces began to set in motion to sell that education website to a larger company. I knew that I was burnt out and tired, but was I ready to hand over the fruits of so many years of work? At the end of the day, I realized that I needed more time in my private life and a much lighter workload, so I signed the papers. My baby is now in the hands of the lovely people at Emerald Expo, and I couldn't be happier to have them care for it in the future.
.
Selling my educational endeavor meant that teaching was going to take a backseat for a couple of years. I had to be OK with that. So much of my career had been about striving for bigger and better in the education world, but where do you go once you've attained the goals you sought to accomplish?
.
The truth is, you rest. I have had several years of reconfiguring what my wedding photography business looks like, spending much-needed quality time with friends and family, falling deeply in love, and recapturing so much of the joy that brought me to this incredible industry in the first place.
.
Except now...now I kind of miss teaching.  I wonder where it will end up fitting into my career in the future...perhaps it's a door that's not firmly shut just yet?

.The other day I posted about some of my favorite cakes that I have seen over my years as a wedding photographer. I don't think it's quite enough just to look at the cakes, maybe we should cut them and eat them?
.
Every single one of these images makes me laugh for a variety of different reasons. I love that my clients feel comfortable enough in front of me to let these funny, open, genuine moments out in front of my camera.
.
The only problem is that now I really really want cake again.

I really miss print competition. The WPPI print comp was the one thing that I looked forward to every single year as a reason to sit down and look at the work I had photographed over the past year, and she was competition entries. Had print comp happened this year, this image definitely would have been one of my entries.
.
However, life changes. Things move on. I've been wondering where I would find my competitive outlet in the future, and I'm still not sure. Regardless, I did sit down and go through my last year of images like I usually did and I found it both frustrating and inspiring.  Per usual.
.
I always want to get better. I pick and pull at all of the perceived flaws in my images, even if they are things that only I would ever see. My relentless drive for perfection has been an asset and a handicap since I began my career.
.
I also have to remember to take the time to celebrate the body of work that I have created. It is so easy to become critical of your own self and your own artistic work and not so easy to pat yourself on the back and acknowledge your ability.
.
I LOVE the work that I created in the past year. While I might not be preparing for a competition, I can certainly be preparing to keep raising the bar on myself again and again in the years to come.

Ohhh, the ceremony.
. 
Whether it's inside or outside, daytime or nighttime, it's the one part of the day where I feel like wedding photographers have the least creative control. Do we use flash if it is too dark? Would it be distracting to the guests? What if we can't move around very much in a limited ceremony setting? What if the ubiquitous church lady has told us that we can't come any closer than the last pew?
.
Here are a handful of some of my favorite ceremony moments over the past years.

Back in the early days of WPPI print competition there was a category called Wedding Humor. I really, really, really wish that category still existed because this image of Ryan throwing the dress and running away in horror has been making me laugh for about a year now.

Destination weddings.
.
It's hard to say when I first "got into" them.  It started when I was living and working in Florida.  It wasn't uncommon to be hired to photograph a wedding on 30-A one day and in Miami the following weekend.
.
As my portfolio started to look more diverse in terms of location, clients started to inquire if I traveled.  At first, it was locations nearby like the Bahamas, but then it started stretching across the country and eventually to even more countries.
.
I love traveling for weddings. Absolutely love it. I love getting to see new locations, experience new traditions and cultures, and be brought along during such a major time in my clients' lives.  I don't get to do it quite as much now that my wedding schedule is so busy, but whenever it works out I'm always excited to pack a bag and hit the road.

I always wonder what kind of contact people want to see on my Instagram account. With followers ranging from photography clients to photographers looking for inspiration, who should I be tailoring my posts to? 
.
Are you looking for education? Do you want to see more behind the scenes about how images are created? Do you want to hear more stories behind my images? 
.
While the constant struggle to figure out the algorithm is a real thing, I never want to chase that while sacrificing the content that the people who come here ACTUALLY want to see.

Nighttime portraits. I freaking love them.
.
Clients often mentioned wanting night portraits, but not knowing exactly how to fit them into the timeline. If your reception is taking place entirely at night, I would suggest ducking out for a few minutes during dinner. This way you aren't missing any dancing or opportunity to mingle, and I promise you won't be gone that long! 
.
Most of the time my nighttime portrait sessions take 10 minutes at the most, and then you're back to the party.  We work quickly and efficiently, both with posing and lighting because we know that while these images are super fun to have they shouldn't take too much away from your wedding day!

It's not fair to any of my clients or subjects or weddings or anything to choose a favorite image of the year. 
.
It's also quite simply impossible because my folder of favorite images has over 300 photographs in it just from 2022 alone.
.
If I had to? Absolutely had to? This portrait of Pierre would be way at the tippy tippy top.

I think that every wedding photographer has certain things that stress them out during the wedding day. My big fear when I first started my career as a photographer was messing something up during the processional.
.
What if I missed a moment? What if everyone's eyes were closed? What if the images weren't in focus? Do you know how hard it is to focus on a moving subject? What if my lighting was bad? What about my composition?
.
As with all things pertaining to wedding photography, I was worrying too much and not trusting myself enough.
.
Now I crouch in the aisle, out of the way of guests, obstructing no one's view of the humans coming down the aisle. I focus, I breathe, I pause. And I am so grateful to be able to capture these moments.

Hey Amanda and Ben, do you remember when we did these engagement pictures in the back hallway of a wedding venue near the entrance to the kitchen right in front of a folding screen?
.
Me, too.
.
(Miss you!)

A wedding ceremony is a beautiful thing, but it's even more beautiful when you and your love walk back down the aisle hand in hand.  Or ducking flower petals. Or walking into the sunset. Or stopping for a kiss. Or just smiling your faces off so hard your muscles hurt the next day.
.
Cheers to all these smiling faces!

I remember the first time I put a grid on my flash and said "holy sh*t". Then I put the grid in the flash behind my subject and said "holy sh*t" again.
.
I'm a creature of habit. I don't love upgrading to new products and tools unless I know that they are going to help me make better images. It takes me a long time to add something new to my arsenal. I'm only angry that it took me as long as it did to discover grids. 
.
Grids, I love you and your little honeycomb goodness.  Thank you for helping me use my flash with even more control.

Even though I could not walk more than one step in any of these pairs of shoes I love them with everything I've got in me.
.
(I spent years trying to learn to love heels but had to eventually admit that it's combat boots and Birkenstocks over here forever. Oh and Hokas, can't forget about the Hokas!)

If you're dreaming of the perfect wedding photos with a stunning city backdrop, then the rooftop area at the Top of the Rock in Rockefeller Center is likely high on your list of potential photo locations. But let me tell you, getting space to yourself in that spot is about as likely as seeing a rat in the subway. 
.
Oh wait, scratch that last one - you'll definitely see rats in the subway.
.
The Top of the Rock is one of the most popular attractions in New York City. It offers badass views of the city from 70 stories up, and it's no wonder that countless couples have chosen it as the perfect spot for their wedding photos. However, this also means that it's one of the busiest places in the city, with tourists and locals alike vying for the perfect Instagram photo.
.
To make matters worse, there will be employees stationed around the rooftop to make sure that everyone is safe and following the rules. This means that any attempt to sneak in a quick photo in a forbidden area will be met with a stern talking to from a security guard, who is definitely not impressed with the fact that you just got married.
.
Despite all of that this is one of my favorite locations in the city. If you are patient and kind people WILL get out of your way, and the wait is always worth it.
.
(Except I almost always get in a leeeeeetle bit of trouble because I always lean just a bit TOO FAR over a railing of some kind and get scolded. Still. Worth.  It.)

Taking silhouette photos is a beautiful way to capture the essence of a person without being too literal. By removing the details and focusing on the shape and contour, you're able to create something graphic and different.
.
There's something magical about the way a silhouette can convey so much emotion with so little detail. It's a reminder that sometimes, less really is more. 
.
Here are some of my favorite silhouettes from over the years.

As a creative wedding photographer, it's important to push myself out of my comfort zone and try new things. And working with light in a different way can be one of the most exciting and rewarding ways to do so.
.
Here I took a chance and experimented with dappled light in a portrait, even though it's not something I usually do. I wanted to create a mood and add some texture to the photo, and the results were just what I was looking for.
.
Of course, stepping out of my comfort zone is never easy. It can be scary and nerve-wracking to try something new, especially when you're used to certain techniques and styles. But that's all part of the fun. You never know what you might discover when you take a risk and try something new.

I've always been drawn to the strange and unusual. And one technique that's always fascinated me is multiple exposures.
.
There's something otherworldly about the way that two images can overlap and blend together, creating something entirely new and unexpected. It's like glimpsing into another dimension - a place where time and space are distorted and anything is possible.
.
Of course, creating multiple exposures isn't easy. It requires a delicate touch and a willingness to experiment and take risks. But for me, the reward is worth the effort!
.
As a lover of horror films, I know that the best stories are the ones that play with reality and bend the rules. And in the world of wedding photography, creating multiple exposures is a way to do just that. It's a way to explore the boundaries of what's possible, and create something truly unique and unforgettable.
.
Here are some of my favorite in-camera multiple exposures throughout the years.

The timeless appeal of a classic black-and-white portrait is undeniable. There's something about the stark contrast and depth of the shadows that evokes a sense of mystery and intrigue, like an untold story lurking just beneath the surface.
.
As a photographer, I'm always drawn to the power of suggestion - the way that the things we don't show can be just as powerful as the things we do.
.
For me, the appeal of a black-and-white portrait is in its ability to capture the essence of a person, free from the distractions of color or context. It's a moment frozen in time, a glimpse into the soul of the subject. And in a world that's constantly changing, that's something truly timeless.

What you choose to wear on your wedding day is important. It's a reflection of who you are, a statement about your style and your personality. And in a world that often tries to force us into narrow definitions of what's beautiful and acceptable, it's important to remember that the most important thing is to be true to yourself.
.
As a photographer, I'm drawn to the idea that we all have a unique story to tell, and the way we present ourselves to the world is an important part of that narrative. The wedding day is a celebration of love, but it's also a celebration of the individuality and complexity of the people getting married.
.
So whether you choose a classic white gown, a black tux, a feather cape, or a bold red suit, what matters is that you feel like yourself. That you feel comfortable and confident and true to who you are. 
.
(But seriously, I wasn't kidding, please wear a feather cape, that would be so rad.)

What better thing is there to do for your one-year anniversary than go live in a van together and drive cross country?

Bill and I spent weeks in the van, breaking only to go to WPPI (where we DID stay in an actual hotel). From horrible windstorms in Texas to a nail in the tire, Horseshoe Bend to an overflowing van toilet somewhere in Albuquerque, we saw it all and then some.

Here are my favorite pictures from the trip.* 

***(Pictures that I took I mean.  Bill hasn't even downloaded his yet. 🙂 )

Dear clients,

As your wedding photographer, I understand how important it is to capture special moments on your wedding day. I also understand that sometimes the most beautiful moments are the ones that happen naturally, without intervention or direction.
.
That's why I believe in being a silent observer. Of course, there are times when I'll guide you and help you pose to create images - I'm never going to leave you wondering what to do with your hands and where to stand! But there are also times when it's important to step back and allow moments to unfold in front of me.
.
When I'm able to observe quietly, I can capture the genuine emotion and authentic interactions that make your day unique. I can create images that tell your love story, ones that will be cherished for generations to come.
.
So while I may not always be front and center, know that I'm there, ready and waiting. Trust that my eye for detail will allow me to capture the magic of your day in a way that is authentic, beautiful, and uniquely yours.

Sincerely,

Me

It took me until my late 30s to find a great group of friends and let me tell you, it was worth the wait. There's nothing quite like being surrounded by people who get you, who support you, who send you memes from the bathroom, and who make you laugh until you wheeze.
.
I have the pleasure of documenting clients with the people they love so dearly - their friends. Seeing the way they interact, the laughter, the joy, and the connection, it's truly heartwarming. It reminds me of the value of good friends, and how important it is to celebrate the people who make our lives better.
.
Capturing these moments is a privilege. It allows me to witness the bonds between people, the ones that endure through thick and thin. And as I work, I'm grateful for my own friends, the ones who waited for me and who continue to make my life better every day.  You know who are.  I think. :)

Central Park is a magical place where you can escape the chaos of the city and pretend you're in a forest. It's like the city planners looked around and said, "you know what we need? A giant green space in the middle of all this. And let's throw in a castle and a zoo while we're at it." It's like the ultimate urban oasis, where you can see squirrels and pigeons and humans all coexisting in harmony. Plus, where else can you find a 15-foot-tall bronze statue of Alice in Wonderland surrounded by giant mushrooms?
.
As a photographer, I love providing my clients with useful information to help them get the most out of their photo sessions. That's why I recently wrote a huge page on my website about the best photo locations in Central Park. I've spent countless hours getting lost over and over in the park, and I'm glad to let my inability to follow Google maps lead to this piece of writing.
.
(Link in stories to the info if you'd like to read it!)

Don't forget to dance like nobody's watching.
.
(Except me, I'm watching.  It's literally my job to watch you. So dance like nobody is watching except uh, me.)

A first look can be a beautiful and intimate moment for a couple on their wedding day. As a photographer, I've seen firsthand how special it can be to have that private moment together before the hustle and bustle of the day takes over. 
.
However, it's important to remember that it's ultimately your decision whether or not to do a first look.
.
Some couples prefer to wait until the ceremony to see each other, and that can be JUST as magical. Your wedding day is all about what feels right for you and your partner. Whatever you choose to do, I'll be there and I'll support your decision.
.
But if you do decide on a first look, I can promise you that it can be a pretty freaking great experience. You'll have a chance to take a deep breath and share a special moment with your partner before the ceremony, and that can be invaluable.
.
Here are some of my favorite first looks throughout the years.

I'm not ready to let go of the first looks juuuust yet, clearly.
.
I can honestly say that there's nothing quite like capturing the honest intimate moments that happen throughout a wedding day. I feel so grateful that my clients trust me to witness and document these oh-so-very private moments.
.
It's a privilege to be able to freeze those little moments in time so that my clients can look back on them years from now and relive the emotions they felt on their special day. So thank you, seriously thank you, for allowing me to bear witness.  It means more than you know.

Grand Central Station is a hot mess. A chaotic web of platforms, trains, people, and noise, all vying for space in one of New York City's most iconic landmarks. But despite the mayhem, it's one of my favorite places to take a portrait of one person at a wedding. Why, you ask? Because it's so damn difficult, that's why.
.
There's something about the challenge of capturing a moment in the midst of such chaos that makes my stubborn self wake UP. I want to show the scene in a way that no one else has, to find the beauty in the madness and make it shine.
.
It's not just the hustle and bustle that makes Grand Central Station a tough place to shoot, though. The lighting is tricky. You MUST have a permit.  You have to work faster than fast.  You can't stop crowds, move people, or get in the way or out you go.
.
But it's that challenge that makes it all worthwhile. When I finally get the shot I'm after, when I've managed to capture a moment of stillness in the chaos, it's a rush like no other. So yes, Grand Central Station is a hot mess, but it's MY hot mess.

Wedding rings are a beautiful tradition that have been around for centuries. They symbolize love, commitment, and the promise of a lifetime together. But honestly? I have to admit, I mostly just love how shiny they are.
.
Collecting jewelry is like piecing together a puzzle. Each charm, chain, and circle of gold represents a moment in time, a memory etched into the metal. As I add to my collection, I can't help but feel like a curator of my own personal museum. These talismans are markers of my life, each one telling a unique story. And when I pass them down to future generations, I know they'll be more than just shiny trinkets. They'll be a legacy, a way to keep those memories alive for years to come.
.
What can be more powerful a talisman or token than a wedding ring?  Here are ten of my very favorites.

“To wear dreams on one’s feet is to begin to give a reality to one’s dreams.”- Roger Vivier
.
Here are some more of my favorite wedding shoes from years past.

Just stopping for a second to announce my love for the RF 50mm f/1.2 lens.
.
The bokeh on this lens is simply utterly bananas gorgeous. Add to it fast autofocus and almost-way-too-sharp optics, this lens actually sat in my bag for nearly a YEAR before I picked it up and fell in love. (What can I say, I move slow). For some reason I'd never been drawn to the 50mm focal length but now?  You'd have to pry this lens out of my hands.*
.
.
.
*(Or just be in the Cornell library at the right time when I accidentally forgot and left it behind a chair and my assistant had to stealthily get back into the library after closing time to get it for me hahahahahahahahahah let's never do that again, @kelseycannici okay?)

What year was this taken?  What lens did I use?  What camera?
.
After a point, does it matter?  I've been aiming to capture timeless moments since 2002, and I feel like this image is a good representative of that approach!
Sunset in the Hamptons. I'm not a huge summer person (any temperature over 70 is too hot for me) but I will make an exception for the Hamptons anytime.

One of the first things I do when entering a new space is to scan for the best sources of natural light.  I then start to envision how I can compose my shots, what angles might work best, and how to incorporate the surrounding elements to tell a story. .
I almost always look for mirrored surfaces - in this case a framed piece of art that perfectly reflected the dress.

As I work hard on writing updated content for my website I get to revisit venues that I love and can't wait to work at again.  I think about the light from this window at least once a week and miss this gorgeous gem of a venue.

I always try my best to make artificial light look as natural as possible. Is this all candlelight?  Did I add any additional light?  And at the end of the day does it matter as long as the image is lovely?
.
.
(FYI there IS an additional light behind her face,  I didn't want to leave you hanging!)

I do not use flatlays at weddings.
.
I know, I know.  It's become super popular.  Lots of photographers even bring "styling kits" to create their detail images. 
.
Not me though.  I prefer to document details as they are, using items important to my clients or found on the scene.  I especially love to document those details ON the humans that will wear them!

social_posts.post_text:
I'm feeling a little tired of Instagram lately.  Anyone else?
.
I love sharing my work.  I get really excited to put things into the world that I think are beautiful, that show the love between two humans, that say "hey, this is who I am and what I can create."
.
As my photography style evolves I've been doing a lot of larger scene work, showcasing a couple in a beautiful space.  Unfortunately that makes my subjects "small" and their faces "small" and Insta doesn't like that so much.
.
Over the past year my work has been shown to less and less eyeballs.  It started to bother me, and I get over it, then it bothers me again, then I get over it.
.
I'm pretty much over it for good now.  Whew.
.

I love "take your boyfriend to work" day.  My partner is also a photographer, and we like to go help each other out when we can.  Holding lights, being a second photographer, it's all fun when you're working with someone you love.
.
It's extra fun when he turns to me and whispers the idea for a photo in my ear...and it's the same image I was just envisioning making.  Those little moments are so special to me.
.

I SERIOUSLY CANNOT HANDLE THIS AND AM SO EXCITED THAT I AM YELLING IN ALL CAPS.
.
Businesses change over time. In the past years, my business has become softer (despite the caps-yelling above), even more caring, and even more passionate about making sure my clients feel loved and welcome. Inclusivity has gone to the top of my business values list. Even the words I use have become gentler, more measured, just MORE.
.
It was time for a new website to reflect that.
.
It's my sincere hope that all feel welcome, that my message comes across with even more clarity, and that the images and words have space to really sing in this new space.
.
I hope you love it as much as I do. Link is above if you'd like to check it out.

501 Union is an aesthetic dream: a perfect blend of modern and vintage for weddings. 
.
The industrial-chic vibe and historic charm make every inch of this Brooklyn-based venue photogenic. From exposed brick walls (which I love so much that I have in my own home!) to the skylight in the reception ballroom, it's a delight to take photos here. I also just really adore the neighborhood - it's just a quick walk from my studio, too!
.

My fourth wedding of 2023 was a total delight.  Lindsey and Esha got ready together at home (delight #1), took their portraits in DUMBO at Brooklyn Bridge Park (delight #2), and had their sweet ceremony and reception at Celestine (delights #3 to infinity).

Brooklyn Bridge Park has always had my heart.  Celestine is now my new obsession - the food is brilliant and the view of Manhattan from their outdoor terrace is spectacular.

This was the most lovely, sweetest wedding to usher in the springtime.  Lindsey and Esha, I'll go back to Celestine with you anytime!

#celestinebrooklyn #celestinewedding #brooklynbridgepark #dumboweddingphotos #nycweddingphotographer

I've had the privilege of capturing some beautiful moments at Oheka Castle, and it's been wayyy too long since I revisited some of my faves! Swipe through for a peek at some of my favorite shots from this stunning venue. 

From the grandeur of the castle's architecture to the lush greenery surrounding it, Oheka Castle is such a theatrically fantastic place for a wedding. Everything that I love to photograph on a wedding day is so amplified here, from grand staircases (note: there are more than one) to tree-lined paths, the massive library to the fantastic getting-ready suite, I have no notes, Oheka.  None.  You're perfect, never change!

#ohekacastle #weddingphotography #castlewedding #weddinggoals #weddingideas #weddinginspiration #weddingphotographer #newyorkweddingphotographer

It was so hard to narrow down my favorite wedding day portraits from 2023 that it's going to be a two-parter! 

The time alone that I have with couples on their wedding day is just so meaningful. Whether before or after the ceremony, the portrait time is such a lovely time for my clients to get to BE ALONE.  They are surrounded by loved ones all day, but the portrait time is theirs and theirs alone.  And that's pretty magical.

I can't help but feel inspired every time I step foot here.  It's gothic and gorgeous, peaceful, and also somehow dramatic.  In short, it's a wedding photographer's dream.
